======================================================================
PART 1: EXACT n=7 — ALL CYCLE TYPES
======================================================================

At n=7: possible cycle lengths are 3, 5, 7
Disjoint pairs: (3,3) only (3+5=8>7, 5+5=10>7)
So α₂ = α₂(3,3) exactly at n=7

Random sampling 200 tournaments at n=7:
  T0: α₁³=10, α₁⁵=0, α₁⁷=0, α₁=10, α₂=7, α₂(3,3)=7, ok=True
  T1: α₁³=9, α₁⁵=0, α₁⁷=0, α₁=9, α₂=6, α₂(3,3)=6, ok=True
  T2: α₁³=7, α₁⁵=0, α₁⁷=0, α₁=7, α₂=1, α₂(3,3)=1, ok=True
  T3: α₁³=12, α₁⁵=2, α₁⁷=0, α₁=14, α₂=8, α₂(3,3)=8, ok=True
  T4: α₁³=11, α₁⁵=2, α₁⁷=0, α₁=13, α₂=8, α₂(3,3)=8, ok=True
  Violations (α₂ > α₁): 0/200
  Max α₂/α₁: 1.0000

======================================================================
PART 2: n=8 — THE LAST BEFORE THE TRANSITION
======================================================================

At n=8: 3+5=8 = n, so (3,5) pairs need 8 vertices = ALL of them
A (3,5) disjoint pair is possible iff the 3 remaining vertices
after removing a 3-cycle form a 5-cycle (impossible: 8-3=5 vertices needed)
Wait: 3-cycle uses 3 vertices, remaining 5 can form a 5-cycle!
So at n=8: α₂ = (3,3) pairs + (3,5) pairs

Random sampling 200 tournaments at n=8:
  T0: α₁³=19, α₁⁵=4, α₁=23, α₂=32 [33=31, 35=1, 55=0], ok=False
  T1: α₁³=10, α₁⁵=1, α₁=11, α₂=4 [33=4, 35=0, 55=0], ok=True
  T2: α₁³=15, α₁⁵=1, α₁=16, α₂=15 [33=15, 35=0, 55=0], ok=True
  T3: α₁³=15, α₁⁵=1, α₁=16, α₂=14 [33=14, 35=0, 55=0], ok=True
  T4: α₁³=16, α₁⁵=3, α₁=19, α₂=21 [33=21, 35=0, 55=0], ok=False
  Violations (α₂ > α₁): 121/200
  Max α₂/α₁: 2.0000
  Worst case: α₁=18, α₂=36
    Breakdown: α₁³=18, α₁⁵=0
    α₂(3,3)=36, α₂(3,5)=0, α₂(5,5)=0

