======================================================================
PART 4: THE CRITICAL QUESTION — DOES α₁ ≥ α₂ ALWAYS HOLD?
======================================================================

The Cauchy-Schwarz proof shows α₁ ≥ α₂ for n ≤ 9
when we restrict to 3-cycles.

But α₂ includes disjoint pairs of ALL cycle types!
At n=8: (3,5) pairs are possible
At n=9: (3,3) and possibly (3,5) if 3+5=8 ≤ 9
At n=10: (3,3), (3,5), (5,5) pairs

Does α₁(full) ≥ α₂(full) still hold?

FOCUSED TEST at n=9 (2000 samples):
  VIOLATION at trial 0: α₁=20, α₂=43, ratio=2.1500
    α₁³=18, α₁⁵=2
    α₂(3,3)=41, α₂(3,5)=2
  VIOLATION at trial 1: α₁=22, α₂=53, ratio=2.4091
    α₁³=21, α₁⁵=1
    α₂(3,3)=51, α₂(3,5)=2
  VIOLATION at trial 2: α₁=13, α₂=16, ratio=1.2308
    α₁³=13, α₁⁵=0
    α₂(3,3)=16, α₂(3,5)=0
  n=9 violations: 1936/2000
  Max α₂/α₁: 3.400000
  Mean α₂/α₁: 2.213921
  Median α₂/α₁: 2.307692

