======================================================================
PART 7: THE MINIMUM 5-CYCLE FRACTION
======================================================================

For the extended Cauchy-Schwarz to work at n=N,
we need f₅ ≥ (√N - 3)/2.

The question: can f₅ be arbitrarily small?
Is there a tournament with many 3-cycles but few 5-cycles?

Searching for tournaments with HIGH 3-cycle to 5-cycle ratio:
  n=7: max 3/5 ratio = 13.000 (3-cyc=13, 5-cyc=1)
       min f₅ = 0.0714 (13 three-cycles, 1 five-cycles)
       678/1000 tournaments have 3-cycles but NO 5-cycles
  n=8: max 3/5 ratio = 18.000 (3-cyc=18, 5-cyc=1)
       min f₅ = 0.0526 (18 three-cycles, 1 five-cycles)
       432/1000 tournaments have 3-cycles but NO 5-cycles
  n=9: max 3/5 ratio = 25.000 (3-cyc=25, 5-cyc=1)
       min f₅ = 0.0385 (25 three-cycles, 1 five-cycles)
       181/1000 tournaments have 3-cycles but NO 5-cycles

======================================================================
PART 8: TRANSITIVE TOURNAMENTS AND MINIMAL CYCLES
======================================================================

The transitive tournament has 0 cycles of any length.
Near-transitive tournaments (1 edge flipped) have few cycles.

n=9 transitive + 1 flip:
  Flip (0,2): 1 three-cycles, 0 five-cycles — ZERO 5-CYCLES!
    α₁=1, α₂=0, ok=True

